  <h2>Zero-Knowledge Password Managers</h2>
  <p>Because you must use a unique, complex password for every single online account, it is impossible for a human to memorize them all. This is where **Password Managers** are essential. A password manager generates, stores, and automatically fills unique, complex passwords for your accounts.</p>
  <p>Top-tier password managers (such as **Bitwarden**, **1Password**, and **Dashlane**) operate on a **Zero-Knowledge Architecture**. This means that your password vault is encrypted *locally* on your device using a "Master Password" that only you know. The password manager's company never receives your Master Password or your decrypted database on their servers. Even if their servers are breached, the hackers only get scrambled, unreadable encrypted vaults that cannot be cracked without your Master Password.</p>

  <h2>Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) Options Compared</h2>
  <p>Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)—or Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)—requires you to provide two or more verification factors to gain access to an account. Even if an attacker steals your password, they cannot access your account without your secondary authentication factor.</p>

  <table>
